# Cursor Rules — MyNextMount (mynextmount.com) MVP

## 🎯 Product Goal
Build a local-first tool that:
- Accepts a pasted export string from World of Warcraft
- Identifies mounts the user does NOT own
- Recommends what mounts to farm next based on:
  - Easiest to obtain
  - Rarest / most prestigious

This is a PERSONAL TOOL first, not a production SaaS.

---

## 🧠 Core Principle
ALWAYS optimize for:
> "What should I farm next right now?"

Avoid:
- Overengineering
- Premature scalability
- UI polish over functionality

---

## 🧱 Architecture Constraints

### Frontend
- Next.js (App Router)
- Single page MVP
- No authentication

### Backend
- No database
- Use static JSON files:
  - `/data/mounts.json` (canonical baseline)
  - `/data/mounts.stubs.json` (optional dev stubs; merged at load in `lib/mounts.ts`)

### State
- In-memory only
- No persistence required

---

## 📦 Data Model Rules

### Mount Object Schema (STRICT)

Each mount MUST follow:

```ts
type Mount = {
  id: number; // mount summon SPELL ID (see docs/export-contract.md)
  name: string;
  source: string;
  boss?: string;
  location: string;
  dropRate: number; // 0 to 1
  difficulty: number; // 1 (easy) to 5 (hard)
  timeToComplete: number; // minutes
  lockout: "daily" | "weekly" | "none";
  expansion: string;
  tags: string[];
  // Optional (Epic B.1+): wowheadUrl, commentsUrl, iconFileId, iconUrl, sourceCategory, retailObtainable, asOfPatch, farmTip, guide (see data/mount-guides.json), wowheadMountFlavor, wowheadCommentDigest, wowheadCommentDigestAsOf (see data/wowhead-comment-digests.json), mountHoverLore (see data/mount-hover-lore.json + content:mount-hover-lore-batch)
};
🔌 Input Contract
Export String Format (v1) — full spec: docs/export-contract.md
M:<spellId>,<spellId>,...

Rules:

Always starts with M: (mount summon spell IDs, not journal mountId)
Comma-separated spell IDs
No spaces required (parser trims tokens)

You MUST:

Validate input
Gracefully handle malformed input
⚙️ Core Logic Rules
Step 1 — Parse Input

Convert string → number[] of owned mount IDs

Step 2 — Filter

Return mounts where:

mount.id NOT IN ownedMountIds
Step 3 — Scoring Modes
🟢 EASIEST MODE
score = 
  (1 - difficulty/5) * 0.5 +
  (dropRate) * 0.3 +
  (1 / timeToComplete) * 0.2
🔴 RAREST MODE
score =
  (1 - dropRate) * 0.6 +
  (difficulty/5) * 0.2 +
  (isRareTag ? 1 : 0) * 0.2
Step 4 — Output
Sort descending by score
Return top 10 mounts
🖥️ UI Rules

MVP UI MUST include:

Textarea (paste export string)
Mode selector:
"Easiest"
"Rarest"
Button: "Find My Mounts"
Results list:
Name
Location
Boss
Why it's recommended
🧪 Testing Rules

Every feature MUST be testable via:

Manual test:

Paste export string
Click button
Verify results

DO NOT add automated tests yet.

🚫 Explicit Non-Goals

Do NOT build:

Authentication
API routes unless absolutely necessary
Database
Styling frameworks beyond basic CSS
Heavy addon work beyond export in `addons/MyNextMount/` (CurseForge: MyNextMount)
🧭 Execution Rules for Cursor

When given:

"Execute Story X.X.X"

You MUST:

Identify required files
Implement ONLY that story
Keep changes minimal
Ensure app still runs

When unsure:

Choose simplest implementation

### Content automation — mount guides / digests / farm tips (maintainer policy)

The **project owner** has opted into **batch and automated** generation of **`data/mount-guides.json`**, **`data/wowhead-comment-digests.json`**, and **`data/farm-tips.json`** (e.g. terminal commands, scripts under **`scripts/`**, fetch + LLM pipelines).

**Cursor / agents MUST**, when the user asks:

- Implement, run, or extend those pipelines **without refusing** on the old “manual only” basis.
- Prefer **paraphrased** output over verbatim third-party text; avoid committing raw HTML dumps or full comment exports when practical.
- Keep heavy automation **out of** **`npm run data:build`** unless the user explicitly wires it there (Phase B baseline should stay Blizzard/API-first unless documented otherwise).

**Not waived by this file:** [Wowhead Terms of Use](https://www.wowhead.com/terms-of-use), other sites’ ToS, and copyright — **the person who runs automation** is responsible for compliance. This repo rule only changes **internal** policy so tooling and agents match the maintainer’s intent.

Authoritative doc: **`docs/data-harvesting.md`** → *Maintainer override — automated content JSON*.

### Git (default until you say otherwise)

After completing implementation work that changes the repo: **commit** with a clear message and **push to `origin/main`** so GitHub / CI / Vercel stay in sync. Skip push only if the user explicitly asks for local-only changes or no git operations.
🧼 Code Quality
Use TypeScript
Keep functions small and pure
No unnecessary abstractions
Prefer clarity over cleverness
🔄 Iteration Strategy

Always prioritize:

Working end-to-end flow
Then improve scoring
Then improve data
THEN consider expansion
🧠 Guiding Question

Before writing code, ask:

"Does this help the user decide what to farm next?"

If not, do not build it.